Question 1

state.of.interest = "California"
lab02 = covid %>%
  filter(state == state.of.interest) %>%
  group_by(county) %>%
  summarise(dailynewcases = cases - lag(cases), fips=fips, date=date, cases=cases) %>%
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'county'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

1.5

## Safe Counties with Less than 100 new cases per 100,000 residents in last 14 Days
safe = joinCalPop %>%
  filter(date >= max(date) - 13) %>%
  group_by(county, POP_ESTIMATE_2019) %>%
  summarise(new14 = sum(dailynewcases))  %>%
  mutate(percapita = new14/(POP_ESTIMATE_2019 / 100000)) %>%
  ungroup() %>% 
  select(county, percapita) %>%
  filter(percapita < 100)  
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'county'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
joinCalPop %>%
  filter(date >= max(date) - 13, county=="Imperial") %>% select(date, cases, dailynewcases, county)

Question 2.1

### Number of Daily New Cases at State Level
states.of.interest = c("California", "New York", "Louisiana", "Florida")
statedata = covid %>%
  filter(state %in% states.of.interest) %>%
  group_by(state, date) %>%
  summarize(statecases = sum(cases, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(newCases = statecases - lag(statecases),
         roll7 = rollmean(newCases, 7, fill = NA, align="right")) %>% 
  ungroup() 
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'state'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
ggplot(statedata, aes(x = date, y = newCases))+
  geom_col(aes(y = newCases), col = NA, fill = "#778899")+
  geom_line(aes(y = roll7, col = state)) +
  facet_wrap(~state) +
  ylim(0, 60000)+
  labs(title = paste("  New Reported Covid Cases by Day \n in", paste(states.of.interest, collapse = ", ")))+
  labs(x = "Date",
       y = "New Cases",
       subtitle = "NY Times Data") +
  theme_economist_white()
## Warning: Removed 9 rows containing missing values (position_stack).

## Question 2.2

## New Reported Cases by day Per Capita
states = data.frame(state_abb = state.abb, region=state.region, state=state.name)
state.abb.data <- inner_join(statedata, states, by = "state")

perCapitaState <- inner_join(PopEst, state.abb.data, by = c("State" = "state_abb"))

stateperCap <- perCapitaState %>% 
  mutate(newCasesperCap = newCases / POP_ESTIMATE_2019,
         perCapmean = roll7 / POP_ESTIMATE_2019) %>% 
  select(State, POP_ESTIMATE_2019, date, statecases,newCases, newCasesperCap, perCapmean, roll7)

ggplot(stateperCap, aes(x = date, y = newCasesperCap)) +
  geom_col(aes(y = newCasesperCap), col = NA, fill = "bisque2")+
  geom_line(aes(y = perCapmean, col = State))+
  facet_wrap(~State) +
  labs(title = paste("  New Reported Covid Cases Per Capita by Day \n in", 
                     paste(states.of.interest, collapse = ", ")))+
  ylim(0, 100)+
  labs(x = "Date",
       y = "New Cases",
       subtitle = "NY Times Data") +
  theme_economist_white()

paste("Scaling by population adjusted the plots relative to their own state populations. California looks relatively the same since this state has the most cases and the largest population. Florida and New York look better because these states have large populations with less cases. Louisiana looks worse since they have a smaller population and more cases relative to their population than the other states.")
